   7\\t- simplified mesh: `config.paths.processed_mesh_dir/<root_id>.ply`\\n     8\\t- optional skeleton: `config.paths.skeletons_raw_dir/<root_id>.swc`\\n     9\\t- surface graph: `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_graph.npz`\\n    10\\t- patch graph: `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_patch_graph.npz`\\n    11\\t- optional sidecars: descriptor and QA JSON written by `scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py`\\n    12\\t\\n    13\\t## Generate a preview\\n    14\\t\\n    15\\tPreview one or more specific root IDs:\\n    16\\t\\n    17\\t```bash\\n    18\\tpython scripts/05_preview_geometry.py --config config/local.yaml --root-id 101 --root-id 102\\n    19\\t```\\n    20\\t\\n    21\\tPreview the active selected subset from `config.paths.selected_root_ids`:\\n    22\\t\\n    23\\t```bash\\n    24\\tpython scripts/05_preview_geometry.py --config config/local.yaml --limit 4\\n    25\\t```\\n    26\\t\\n    27\\tEquivalent Make target:\\n    28\\t\\n    29\\t```bash\\n    30\\tmake preview CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\n    31\\t```\\n    32\\t\\n    33\\tThe output location is deterministic for the exact root-id set. By default the\\n    34\\tscript writes to:\\n    35\\t\\n    36\\t```text\\n    37\\tconfig.paths.geometry_preview_dir/root-ids-<sorted-root-ids>/\\n    38\\t```\\n    39\\t\\n    40\\tExample:\\n    41\\t\\n    42\\t```text\\n    43\\tdata/processed/previews/root-ids-101-102/index.html\\n    44\\tdata/processed/previews/root-ids-101-102/summary.json\\n    45\\tdata/processed/previews/root-ids-101-102/root_ids.txt\\n    46\\t```\\n    47\\t\\n    48\\tThat makes the report path stable enough to reference from run logs, ticket\\n    49\\tnotes, or review comments.\\n    50\\t\\n    51\\t## What the report shows\\n    52\\t\\n    53\\tEach root section keeps the following in one place:\\n    54\\t\\n    55\\t- raw mesh wireframe\\n    56\\t- simplified mesh wireframe\\n    57\\t- skeleton projection or an explicit unavailable marker\\n    58\\t- surface graph projection\\n    59\\t- patch graph projection\\n    60\\t- bundle summary metrics, artifact paths, and QA highlights\\n    61\\t\\n    62\\tThe HTML is fully static and does not require a notebook server, Neuroglancer,\\n    63\\tor FlyWire access.\\n    64\\t\\n    65\\t## Reviewer checklist\\n    66\\t\\n    67\\tReviewers should look for:\\n    68\\t\\n    69\\t- raw vs simplified mesh silhouette staying broadly consistent rather than collapsing or drifting\\n    70\\t- skeleton presence matching expectations for that neuron and following the same gross orientation as the meshes when available\\n    71\\t- surface graph coverage matching the simplified geometry instead of showing obvious holes or disconnected clutter\\n    72\\t- patch graph being non-empty and spatially distributed rather than collapsing to one dominant patch unless that is expected\\n    73\\t- QA warnings or failures that suggest simplification drift, patch coverage gaps, or coarse graph degeneracy\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-005_Ship_offline_geometry_preview_tooling_for_raw_simplified_skeleton_and_patchified_assets/stdout.jsonl:104:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_60\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"nl -ba README.md | sed -n '60,380p'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"    60\\tflywire_wave_repo/\\n    61\\t├── README.md\\n    62\\t├── AGENTS.md\\n    63\\t├── requirements.txt\\n    64\\t├── pyproject.toml\\n    65\\t├── Makefile\\n    66\\t├── .env.example\\n    67\\t├── config/\\n    68\\t│   ├── milestone_1_design_lock.yaml\\n    69\\t│   └── visual_subset.example.yaml\\n    70\\t├── docs/\\n    71\\t│   ├── geometry_preview.md\\n    72\\t│   ├── milestones.md\\n    73\\t│   ├── pipeline_notes.md\\n    74\\t│   └── subset_presets.md\\n    75\\t├── manifests/\\n    76\\t│   └── examples/\\n    77\\t│       └── milestone_1_demo.yaml\\n    78\\t├── schemas/\\n    79\\t│   └── milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json\\n    80\\t├── scripts/\\n    81\\t│   ├── 00_verify_access.py\\n    82\\t│   ├── build_registry.py\\n    83\\t│   ├── 01_select_subset.py\\n    84\\t│   ├── 02_fetch_meshes.py\\n    85\\t│   ├── 03_build_wave_assets.py\\n    86\\t│   ├── 04_validate_manifest.py\\n    87\\t│   ├── 05_preview_geometry.py\\n    88\\t│   └── setup_flywire_token.py\\n    89\\t├── src/\\n    90\\t│   └── flywire_wave/\\n    91\\t│       ├── __init__.py\\n    92\\t│       ├── config.py\\n    93\\t│       ├── io_utils.py\\n    94\\t│       ├── manifests.py\\n    95\\t│       ├── mesh_pipeline.py\\n    96\\t│       ├── registry.py\\n    97\\t│       └── selection.py\\n    98\\t├── tests/\\n    99\\t│   ├── test_manifest_validation.py\\n   100\\t│   └── test_registry.py\\n   101\\t├── flywire_codex/\\n   102\\t└── data/\\n   103\\t    ├── raw/\\n   104\\t    │   └── codex/\\n   105\\t    ├── interim/\\n   106\\t    └── processed/\\n   107\\t```\\n   108\\t\\n   109\\t## FlyWire Authentication\\n   110\\t\\n   111\\tThis repo uses two separate auth contexts:\\n   112\\t\\n   113\\t- **FlyWire Codex** (`codex.flywire.ai`) for browser/UI access and bulk CSV/static downloads\\n   114\\t- **CAVE / FlyWire API** for local programmatic access through `caveclient`, `fafbseg`, and the repo scripts that read `FLYWIRE_TOKEN` from `.env`\\n   115\\t\\n   116\\tBeing signed into **FlyWire Codex** in the browser does **not** automatically configure local Python access. The `FLYWIRE_TOKEN` value in `.env` should be your **FlyWire/CAVE API token**.\\n   117\\t\\n   118\\tRecommended setup flow:\\n   119\\t\\n   120\\t1. Copy the example env file:\\n   121\\t\\n   122\\t```bash\\n   123\\tcp .env.example .env\\n   124\\t```\\n   125\\t\\n   126\\t2. Launch the helper script:\\n   127\\t\\n   128\\t```bash\\n   129\\tpython scripts/setup_flywire_token.py\\n   130\\t```\\n   131\\t\\n   132\\tThis opens the existing-token page first. If you specifically need to mint a new token, run:\\n   133\\t\\n   134\\t```bash\\n   135\\tpython scripts/setup_flywire_token.py --new-token\\n   136\\t```\\n   137\\t\\n   138\\tCreating a new token may invalidate the previous one.\\n   139\\t\\n   140\\t3. Copy the token from the browser page.\\n   141\\t4. Paste it into `.env` as `FLYWIRE_TOKEN=...`, or rerun the helper with `--write-env` to update `.env` interactively.\\n   142\\t5. Optional: after installing dependencies, save the same token to local CAVE secret storage with `caveclient` if you want machine-wide auth for `caveclient` / `fafbseg`.\\n   143\\t6. Rerun access verification:\\n   144\\t\\n   145\\t```bash\\n   146\\tpython scripts/00_verify_access.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   147\\t```\\n   148\\t\\n   149\\tIf FlyWire's materialization service is temporarily down, the verifier will now\\n   150\\treport that as an upstream outage while still confirming whether your token works\\n   151\\tagainst the global info service. Add `--require-materialize` if you want that\\n   152\\tcase to return a non-zero exit code.\\n   153\\t\\n   154\\tThis keeps the auth split explicit: **FlyWire Codex** handles website browsing/downloads, while `FLYWIRE_TOKEN` handles local API access.\\n   155\\t\\n   156\\t## Quick start\\n   157\\t\\n   158\\t### 1) Create environment\\n   159\\t\\n   160\\t```bash\\n   161\\tgit submodule update --init --recursive\\n   162\\tmake bootstrap\\n   163\\t```\\n   164\\t\\n   165\\tInitialize the pinned `flywire_codex/` submodule once after cloning, then run `make bootstrap` to create `.venv/` if needed, upgrade `pip`, and install the repo in editable mode via [`pyproject.toml`](pyproject.toml).\\n   166\\t\\n   167\\tManual equivalent:\\n   168\\t\\n   169\\t```bash\\n   170\\tpython -m venv .venv\\n   171\\tsource .venv/bin/activate\\n   172\\tpython -m pip install --upgrade pip\\n   173\\tpython -m pip install -e .\\n   174\\t```\\n   175\\t\\n   176\\t### 2) Set up FlyWire authentication\\n   177\\t\\n   178\\t```bash\\n   179\\tcp .env.example .env\\n   180\\tpython scripts/setup_flywire_token.py\\n   181\\t```\\n   182\\t\\n   183\\tThen copy the token from the browser page into `.env` as `FLYWIRE_TOKEN=...`, or rerun the helper with `--write-env` to update `.env` interactively.\\n   184\\t\\n   185\\t### 3) Download the FlyWire Codex metadata exports\\n   186\\t\\n   187\\tPlace the files you downloaded from FlyWire Codex into:\\n   188\\t\\n   189\\t```text\\n   190\\tdata/raw/codex/\\n   191\\t```\\n   192\\t\\n   193\\tRecommended registry inputs:\\n   194\\t\\n   195\\t```text\\n   196\\tdata/raw/codex/classification.csv\\n   197\\tdata/raw/codex/cell_types.csv\\n   198\\tdata/raw/codex/connections_filtered.csv\\n   199\\tdata/raw/codex/neurotransmitter_type_predictions.csv\\n   200\\t```\\n   201\\t\\n   202\\t### 4) Copy the example config\\n   203\\t\\n   204\\t```bash\\n   205\\tcp config/visual_subset.example.yaml config/local.yaml\\n   206\\t```\\n   207\\t\\n   208\\tAll entries under `config.paths` resolve from the repository root, not from\\n   209\\tthe caller's current working directory. You can run the pipeline from another\\n   210\\tdirectory as long as `--config` points to the right file, for example:\\n   211\\t\\n   212\\t```bash\\n   213\\tpython /abs/path/to/flywire_wave_repo/scripts/build_registry.py \\\\\\n   214\\t  --config /abs/path/to/flywire_wave_repo/config/local.yaml\\n   215\\t```\\n   216\\t\\n   217\\t### 5) Verify access\\n   218\\t\\n   219\\t```bash\\n   220\\tpython scripts/00_verify_access.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   221\\t```\\n   222\\t\\n   223\\t### 6) Build the canonical registry\\n   224\\t\\n   225\\tThis normalizes the local Codex exports into one neuron registry, one\\n   226\\tconnectivity registry, and a provenance JSON with pinned snapshot/materialization\\n   227\\tmetadata plus input file fingerprints.\\n   228\\t\\n   229\\t```bash\\n   230\\tpython scripts/build_registry.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   231\\t```\\n   232\\t\\n   233\\tThis writes:\\n   234\\t\\n   235\\t```text\\n   236\\tdata/interim/registry/neuron_registry.csv\\n   237\\tdata/interim/registry/connectivity_registry.csv\\n   238\\tdata/interim/registry/registry_provenance.json\\n   239\\t```\\n   240\\t\\n   241\\t### 7) Select a subset to mesh\\n   242\\t\\n   243\\tThe Milestone 4 selector is now preset-driven. The sample config defines three\\n   244\\tnamed presets:\\n   245\\t\\n   246\\t- `motion_minimal`\\n   247\\t- `motion_medium`\\n   248\\t- `motion_dense`\\n   249\\t\\n   250\\tEach run writes a root-id list, selected-neuron CSV, stats JSON, manifest JSON,\\n   251\\tand a lightweight Markdown/Mermaid preview under `data/interim/subsets/<preset>/`.\\n   252\\tThe active preset also refreshes `paths.selected_root_ids` so downstream mesh and\\n   253\\tasset steps can switch inputs by config alone.\\n   254\\t\\n   255\\t```bash\\n   256\\tpython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   257\\t```\\n   258\\t\\n   259\\tSelect a specific preset:\\n   260\\t\\n   261\\t```bash\\n   262\\tpython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml --preset motion_dense\\n   263\\t```\\n   264\\t\\n   265\\tGenerate every preset declared in the config:\\n   266\\t\\n   267\\t```bash\\n   268\\tpython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml --all-presets\\n   269\\t```\\n   270\\t\\n   271\\tThis writes the active root-id list to something like:\\n   272\\t\\n   273\\t```text\\n   274\\tdata/interim/root_ids_visual_sample.txt\\n   275\\t```\\n   276\\t\\n   277\\tAnd writes per-preset reports to:\\n   278\\t\\n   279\\t```text\\n   280\\tdata/interim/subsets/\\n   281\\t```\\n   282\\t\\n   283\\t### 8) Fetch meshes + skeletons\\n   284\\t\\n   285\\t```bash\\n   286\\tpython scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   287\\t```\\n   288\\t\\n   289\\tThis downloads raw per-neuron assets into:\\n   290\\t\\n   291\\t```text\\n   292\\tdata/interim/meshes_raw/\\n   293\\tdata/interim/skeletons_raw/\\n   294\\t```\\n   295\\t\\n   296\\t### 9) Build wave-ready mesh assets\\n   297\\t\\n   298\\t```bash\\n   299\\tpython scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   300\\t```\\n   301\\t\\n   302\\tThis creates:\\n   303\\t- simplified meshes,\\n   304\\t- sparse adjacency,\\n   305\\t- graph Laplacians,\\n   306\\t- an example active patch per neuron.\\n   307\\t\\n   308\\tOutputs land in:\\n   309\\t\\n   310\\t```text\\n   311\\tdata/processed/\\n   312\\t```\\n   313\\t\\n   314\\t### 10) Generate an offline geometry preview report\\n   315\\t\\n   316\\t```bash\\n   317\\tpython scripts/05_preview_geometry.py --config config/local.yaml --root-id 720575940000000001\\n   318\\t```\\n   319\\t\\n   320\\tIf you omit `--root-id`, the preview script reads `paths.selected_root_ids`.\\n   321\\tReports write to a deterministic directory under:\\n   322\\t\\n   323\\t```text\\n   324\\tdata/processed/previews/\\n   325\\t```\\n   326\\t\\n   327\\tEach preview directory contains a static `index.html`, `summary.json`, and the\\n   328\\texact `root_ids.txt` used for that report. See [`docs/geometry_preview.md`](docs/geometry_preview.md)\\n   329\\tfor the reviewer checklist and a few common invocation patterns.\\n   330\\t\\n   331\\t## What “meshing for the simulation” means here\\n   332\\t\\n   333\\tFor each selected root ID, this scaffold does:\\n   334\\t\\n   335\\t1. fetch full-resolution FlyWire mesh,\\n   336\\t2. simplify it to a target face budget,\\n   337\\t3. build a sparse surface graph from triangle connectivity,\\n   338\\t4. compute a graph Laplacian,\\n   339\\t5. choose an example local patch that can become the wave solver’s active region,\\n   340\\t6. save everything as `.npz` / `.json` / `.ply`.\\n   341\\t\\n   342\\tThat is enough to support:\\n   343\\t- mesh-resolved wave experiments,\\n   344\\t- branch/patch-local dynamics,\\n   345\\t- synapse-to-patch mapping later,\\n   346\\t- selective promotion of only the currently active neurons.\\n   347\\t\\n   348\\t## Milestone 1 design-lock artifacts\\n   349\\t\\n   350\\tMilestone 1 is treated here as a design/specification milestone rather than a proof-of-effect milestone.\\n   351\\t\\n   352\\t- Roadmap and detailed milestone planning: [`docs/milestones.md`](docs/milestones.md)\\n   353\\t- Machine-readable design lock and success criteria: [`config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml`](config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml)\\n   354\\t- Example demo manifest: [`manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml`](manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml)\\n   355\\t- Manifest schema: [`schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json`](schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json)\\n   356\\t\\n   357\\tValidate the example manifest with:\\n   358\\t\\n   359\\t```bash\\n   360\\tmake validate-manifest\\n   361\\t```\\n   362\\t\\n   363\\tor:\\n   364\\t\\n   365\\t```bash\\n   366\\tpython3 scripts/04_validate_manifest.py \\\\\\n   367\\t  --manifest manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml \\\\\\n   368\\t  --schema schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json \\\\\\n   369\\t  --design-lock config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml\\n   370\\t```\\n   371\\t\\n   372\\t## Suggested first run for your project\\n   373\\t\\n   374\\tDo **not** start by meshing hundreds or thousands of neurons.\\n   375\\t\\n   376\\tA good first pass is:\\n   377\\t- 10–25 visual neurons,\\n   378\\t- simplify each to ~10k–20k faces,\\n   379\\t- use one active patch per neuron,\\n   380\\t- test your wave solver on the patch graph before scaling up.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-005_Ship_offline_geometry_preview_tooling_for_raw_simplified_skeleton_and_patchified_assets/stdout.jsonl:110:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_63\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"nl -ba Makefi